    <div id="cmnt_711807" class="comments-box">
        <div class="post-info">
            <div class="post-info-img"><a href="https://www.inspire.com/groups/stop-sarcoidosis/member/teeteeme/"><img src="/usr_res/teeteeme/img/prof/m" alt="teeteeme" height="75" width="75" /></a></div>
            <ul>
                <li class="by">By <a href="https://www.inspire.com/groups/stop-sarcoidosis/member/teeteeme/">teeteeme</a></li>
                <li class="by">Reply 711807</li>
                <li class="by">January 22, 2010 at  2:02 pm</li>
                <li class="by"><a href="https://www.inspire.com/groups/stop-sarcoidosis/discussion/the-spoon-theory-read-this-youll-be-glad-you-did/reply/711807/flag/">Report post</a></li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <p>I also get people who say you don&#39;t look sick, all the time!! my answer is &quot;would it make you feel better if I did?&quot; &quot;am I supposed to look like crap 24/7?&quot;  Shock value, if nothing else, it gives me satisfaction. I have lost so many friends, because I am sick, and they just don&#39;t &quot;get it&quot;. My first husband didn&#39;t, he found sympathy in another woman&#39;s arms, while still sleeping in my bed. My second husband and I met when I was in remission. He knew all about it, and when I got sick again, and it was 10x worse than the 1st time, it was hard. sometimes it still is. My family though, is amazing. They totally &quot;get it&quot;.  They educated themselves right along with me from day one. and never questioned or doubted me for a second. For that I am truly blessed.  I have been so sick the last two years, I rarely even go out unless it is a dr. appt.  My one girlfriend comes to see me, calls everyday, but the rest, well lets just say, its too hard being friends with someone who can&#39;t go out drinking with them. Then there is an what I call outer layer of friends, who you have never been really close with but you are always happy to see them. Those friends seem to understand and care more. They always send messages with my husband when they see him.<br />
   My advice to everyone who has naysayers is, to tell them, &quot;when you want to educate yourself about sarcoidosis, let me know, until then, don&#39;t offer advice or suggestions, because you don&#39;t know what you are talking about, and your suggestions could harm me medically, and make my situation worse than it already is.&quot;   If you want you can even print out a few key articles or posts that are relevant to you. Don&#39;t give too much too fast, that it is overwhelming. Good luck.</p>
